result.execSummary:
The defendant Daniel A Dewitt Jr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Daniel A Dewitt in court.  Chad A. Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Probation Agent Shelly Trimble appears by telephone.
Atty Hendee states that the defendant is still owing restitution; current discharge date is April 28, 2017.    Court advises defendant of right to an attorney.  Defendant understands and would like to proceed without an Attorney.
Court questions Agent Trimble.  Ms. Trimble confirms payments from the defendant.  Atty Hendee provides the court with the outstanding balance report.  Defendant does not contest the report.  Atty Hendee asks for a 2 year extension of probation and asks for the 30 days stay to be lifted.
Ms. Trimble responds.  Defendant states that he has tried to make good faith payments.  Defendant states that he is working.

BY THE COURT:  Court finds the defendant has not made good faith effort; court extends Probation for two years until April 28, 2019.
Court will continue the stay with conditions.  If defendant does not comply with the conditions of the stay; the Agent may petition the court to lift the stay.  No further hearing will be needed if the stay is lifted.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Daniel A Dewitt in court with attorney Jeffrey T Haase.  Chad A Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Atty Hendee states plea agreement.  Defendant will waive his right to preliminary hearing.  Defendant to enter plea to Ct 1.  Cts 2-3 will be dismissed and read-in.  Atty Haase agrees.
Defendant waives right to preliminary hearing.  Court questions defendant on his waiver.  BY THE COURT:  Court finds probable cause that a felony was committed and this defendant committed it.  Case bound over for trial or further proceedings.  State files Information.  Atty Haase received the Information and waives it's reading.  
Defendant enters No Contest plea to Ct. 1.   Court questions defendant regarding plea. Advises of Constitutional Rights and elements of the charge.  Court finds plea made knowingly, voluntarily & Intelligently.  Court relies on the criminal complaint for a factual basis.  BY THE COURT:  Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.  Court accepts defendant's plea and finds defendant guilty of Ct 1.  Counts 2-3 are dismissed and read-in.
Counsel make sentencing arguments.  Defendant makes statement to the Court.
BY THE COURT:  Sentence withheld, defendant placed on probation for a period of 3 years with the following conditions:
*Pay court costs of $268.00.  *Submit DNA sample and pay surcharge of $250.00.  *Pay restitution in the amount of $16,347.91.  *Maintain full-time employment or complete job searches as recommended by Marquette County Child Support Agency.  *Continue making current child support payments plus $100 toward arrears each month.  *Serve 30 days in the Marquette County Jail with Huber.  That sentence is stayed as long he he remains current on his child support payments.  Probation may request the stay be lifted if conditions are not complied with.
  **Court advises defendant that they have been convicted of a Felony and advises rights of voting privileges and of owning a firearm.
